label.value: decreased pre-tRNA level during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more transfer RNA precursor(s) (pre-tRNA) measured in a cell is lower than normal. Total pre-tRNA or a specific pre-tRNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased pre-tRNA level during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more transfer RNA precursor(s) (pre-tRNA) measured in a cell is higher than normal. Total pre-tRNA or a specific pre-tRNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal pre-tRNA level during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of one or more transfer RNA precursor(s) (pre-tRNA) measured in a cell that is subject to nitrogen starvation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total pre-tRNA or a specific pre-tRNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased histone H3-K4 trimethylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which trimethylation of lysine at position 4 of histone H3 in heterochromatin at subtelomeric regions occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: increased histone H4-K16 acetylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which acetylation of lysine at position 16 of histone H4 in heterochromatin at subtelomeric regions occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased histone H4-K20 dimethylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which dimethylation of lysine at position 20 of histone H4 in heterochromatin at subtelomeric regions occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased promoter-enhancer looping during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which promoter-enhancer looping occurs to a lower extent than normal when the cell is subject to glucose starvation. Promoter-enhancer looping is mediated by interactions between proteins bound to DNA at promoters and at enhancers, or by a single protein binding at both sites.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: decreased chromatin binding at promoter element during glucose starvation

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) at one or more specific promoter element(s) is decreased when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: increased chromatin binding at promoter element during glucose starvation

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) at one or more specific promoter element(s) is increased when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: normal chromatin binding at promoter element during glucose starvation

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) at one or more specific promoter element(s) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: protein absent from cell during mitotic G1 phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell is too low to detect during G1 phase of the mitotic cell cycle. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal meiotic chromosome organization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which chromosome organization is abnormal during the meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: abnormal centromere detachment from spindle pole body during meiotic chromosome organization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which centromeres do not detach properly from the spindle pole body (SPB) during the meiotic cell cycle. Normally, centromeres are located at the SPB during mitotic interphase, and upon entering meiosis, telomeres cluster at the SPB, followed by centromere detachment from the SPB.

label.value: increased transcription during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription occurs to a greater extent than normal during a cellular response to hydroxyurea. All genes, or a specific subset of genes, may be affected.

label.value: normal transcription during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription occurs to a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) extent during a cellular response to hydroxyurea. All genes, or a specific subset of genes, may be measured.

label.value: abolished meiotic cell cycle DNA replication checkpoint

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which cell cycle regulation mediated by the meiotic cell cycle DNA replication checkpoint does not occur under conditions that normally trigger the checkpoint signaling and response. The meiotic DNA replication checkpoint normally prevents the initiation of meiotic nuclear division until pre-meiotic DNA replication is complete.

label.value: normal activation of meiotic cell cycle DNA replication checkpoint

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the meiotic cell cycle DNA replication checkpoint is activated at a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) frequency, under conditions that cause checkpoint activation in wild-type cells. The meiotic DNA replication checkpoint delays the meiotic nuclear division until pre-meiotic DNA replication is complete.

definition.value: Checkpoint activation in a mutant usually implies that the mutation is causing problems that the checkpoint detects.

label.value: abnormal protein phosphorylation during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, is abnormal during the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein phosphorylation in absence of meiotic DNA replication checkpoint arrest

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins occurs to a lower extent than normal during the meiotic cell cycle, in cells that have not arrested the meiotic cell cycle under conditions that normally trigger meiotic DNA replication checkpoint signaling and response.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased cyclin-dependent protein kinase activity in absence of meiotic DNA replication checkpoint arrest

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a cyclin-dependent protein kinase activity is increased during the meiotic cell cycle, in cells that have not arrested the meiotic cell cycle under conditions that normally trigger meiotic DNA replication checkpoint signaling and response.

label.value: increased protein degradation in absence of meiotic DNA replication checkpoint arrest

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of protein degradation is increased during the meiotic cell cycle, in cells that have not arrested the meiotic cell cycle under conditions that normally trigger meiotic DNA replication checkpoint signaling and response.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal kinetochore disassembly during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which kinetochore disassembly is abnormal during prophase of meiosis I. Normally, outer kinetochore components delocalize from the centromere during bouquet formation in meiotic prophase I.

definition.value: Sister chromatids may separate in meiosis I due to problems with either cohesion or kinetochore attachment to microtubules. Therefore consider also annotating to 'abnormal attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore involved in homologous chromosome segregation' (FYPO:0000209), 'decreased meiotic sister chromatid cohesion' (FYPO:0002093), or 'merotelic kinetochore attachment during meiosis I' (FYPO:0005638).

label.value: mislocalized actin cortical patches

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which a cell has actin cortical patches in one or more abnormal locations.

label.value: dispersed actin cortical patch localization during mating

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which actin cortical patches are localized throughout the cell cortex during mating. Normally, actin cortical patches concentrate in the mating projection tip and conjugation bridge during cell fusion, and then disperse after karyogamy.

label.value: abolished protein localization to prospore septin ring

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the prospore septin ring does not occur.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to prospore septin ring

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the prospore septin ring is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased cellular phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate measured in a cell is lower than normal.

label.value: decreased phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself binds phosphatidylinositol-3-phosphate less than wild type, or that a mutation in one gene decreases phosphatidylinositol-3-phosphate binding by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: prospore membrane formation excluding nucleus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the prospore membrane forms, and may complete closure, without enclosing a nucleus; one or more nuclei may be present in the ascus, not enclosed by any prospore membrane.

label.value: prospore formation with septin ring dissociated from prospore membrane

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the septin ring does not associate with the prospore membrane during prospore membrane formation and closure. Normally, the septin ring forms in close association with the assembling prospore membrane.

label.value: resistance to spermidine

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of spermidine than normal.

label.value: sensitive to Rbin-1

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to Rbin-1. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of Rbin-1 that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: resistance to Rbin-1

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of Rbin-1 than normal.

label.value: decreased protein level in large ribosomal subunit precursor

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of a protein measured in a complex that is a precursor of the large ribosomal subunit is lower than normal.

definition.value: Use this term for cases where the relative abundance of one or more specific proteins in the proteasome is decreased, altering the proteasome stoichiometry. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased level of carbohydrate metabolism gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more carbohydrate metabolism RNAs measured in a cell is higher than normal (i.e. higher than observed in wild-type cells). Carbohydrate metabolism RNAs are transcribed from genes whose products are involved in metabolism of one or more carbohydrates.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: tubular vacuole morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which vacuoles tubule-shaped.

label.value: normal growth on cobalt

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing cobalt ions.

label.value: normal growth on manganese

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing manganese ions.

label.value: abnormal poly(A)-specific ribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of poly(A)-specific ribonuclease activity is abnormal.

label.value: decreased poly(A)-specific ribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of poly(A)-specific ribonuclease activity is decreased.

label.value: normal poly(A)-specific ribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of poly(A)-specific ribonuclease activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: meiotic drive suppression

value.value: A biological process phenotype in which meiotic drive occurs to a lower extent than normal, or does not occur at all, despite the presence of a gene or allele that normally causes drive. Meiotic drive results in the unequal transmission of alleles, haplotypes, or chromosomes from a parental genome to such that are unequally represented (i.e. the "driver" is overrepresented) among the surviving products of meiosis.

label.value: lipid droplets present in normal numbers

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell contains a normal number of lipid droplets.

label.value: abolished urease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which urease activity is absent.

label.value: altered meiotic drive suppression specificity

value.value: A biological process phenotype in which the specificity between a meiotic driver gene and a drive suppressor gene differs from that observed when both genes are wild type. Meiotic drive results in the unequal transmission of alleles, haplotypes, or chromosomes from a parental genome to such that are unequally represented (i.e. the "driver" is overrepresented) among the surviving products of meiosis.

label.value: inviable branched, swollen vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is inviable, branched, and has a larger volume than normal. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.

label.value: abolished protein localization to actin cortical patch, with protein mislocalized to nucleus

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to actin cortical patches is abolished, and some of the protein is present in the nucleus instead.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to actin cortical patch, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasm

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to actin cortical patches is abolished, and some of the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: delayed onset of cell separation after cytokinesis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cell separation after cytokinesis begins later than normal.

label.value: normal nuclear MIS12/MIND complex binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to the nuclear MIS12/MIND complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with a protein complex that is assayed in a mutant, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
